dsDescriptionValue.value:
This submission includes publicly available data extracted in its original form. Please reference the Related Publication listed here for source and citation information.
If you have questions about the underlying data stored here, please contact the EPA about Ingredients used in Pesticide Products (pesticidequestions@epa.gov). If you have questions or recommendations related to this metadata entry and extracted data, please contact the CAFE Data Management team at: climatecafe@bu.edu.
"The Pesticide Product Information System (PPIS) contains information concerning all pesticide products registered in the United States. It includes registrant name and address, chemical ingredients, toxicity category, product names, distributor brand names, site/pest uses, pesticidal type, formulation code, and registration status. The files that make up PPIS are ASCII files (ASCII is a code that has been used since the 1960s for information transfer). Interested parties may access them using a variety of database and spreadsheet software. The files on this page are presented in ASCII to enable interested parties to access them using a variety of database and spreadsheet software."
Quote from https://www.epa.gov/ingredients-used-pesticide-products/pesticide-product-information-system-ppis

The Pesticide Product Information System (PPIS) contains information concerning all pesticide products registered in the United States. It includes registrant name and address, chemical ingredients, signal word, product names, distributor brand names, site/pest uses, pesticidal type, formulation code, and registration status.
These Extensible Markup Language (XML) files are being made available to the public to enable interested parties to download all or any part of the pesticide product information, and develop customized queries and reports. Organizations often request that the Office of Pesticide Programs provide copies of these files in slightly different formats, requiring OPP staff to perform time consuming special retrievals. By presenting these files in a standard format, OPP is providing the same information in the same format to all interested parties.
